^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his @E@3important instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls" which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you will find many more.|fp|2|at|

**  Once partner picks a defense, best you stick with it, unless there is a good reason not to.

**  In general, when you have two alternative lines, and you can figure out the odds, pick the play that gives you better odds.

**  Leading an ace or away from an ace is usually not a good idea, as I have said many times. And leading a singleton trump, often gives away a trick.

**  The reason you discount high cards in the opponents suit is that it is less likely that partner has honors in that suit, and combinations of honors work much better than isolated honors.



